[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The purpose of early image processing was to improve the quality of the image.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] In image processing, the input is a low-quality image, and the output is an image with improved quality.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Common image processing includes image enhancement, restoration, encoding, and compression.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The first successful application was the American Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL).
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] They used image processing techniques such as geometric correction, gradation transformation, noise removal, etc. on the thousands of lunar photos sent back by the Space Detector Ranger 7 in 1964, taking into account the position of the Sun and the environment of the Moon.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The impact of the successful mapping of the Moon's surface map by the computer has been a success.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Later, more complex image processing was performed on the nearly 100,000 photos sent back by the spacecraft, so that the topographic map, color map and panoramic mosaic of the Moon were obtained, which achieved extraordinary results and laid a solid foundation for human landing on the Moon.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The cost of processing was fairly high, however, with the computing equipment of that era.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] That changed in the 1970s, when digital image processing proliferated as cheaper computers and dedicated hardware became available.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] This led to images being processed in real-time, for some dedicated problems such as television standards conversion.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] As general-purpose computers became faster, they started to take over the role of dedicated hardware for all but the most specialized and computer-intensive operations.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] With the fast computers and signal processors available in the 2000s, digital image processing has become the most common form of image processing, and is generally used because it is not only the most versatile method, but also the cheapest.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The basis for modern image sensors is metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, This led to the development of digital semiconductor image sensors, including the charge-coupled device (CCD) and later the CMOS sensor.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The charge-coupled device was invented by Willard S.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] While researching MOS technology, they realized that an electric charge was the analogy of the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The CCD is a semiconductor circuit that was later used in the first digital video cameras for television broadcasting.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The NMOS active-pixel sensor (APS) was invented by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] This was enabled by advances in MOS semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The NMOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) was later developed by Eric Fossum's team at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] By 2007, sales of CMOS sensors had surpassed CCD sensors.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] MOS image sensors are widely used in optical mouse technology.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The first optical mouse, invented by Richard F.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Lyon at Xerox in 1980, used a 5 μm NMOS integrated circuit sensor chip.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Since the first commercial optical mouse, the IntelliMouse introduced in 1999, most optical mouse devices use CMOS sensors.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] An important development in digital image compression technology was the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a lossy compression technique first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] DCT compression became the basis for JPEG, which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group in 1992.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] JPEG compresses images down to much smaller file sizes, and has become the most widely used image file format on the Internet.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Its highly efficient DCT compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos, with several billion JPEG images produced every day as of 2015.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Medical imaging techniques produce very large amounts of data, especially from CT, MRI and PET modalities.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] As a result, storage and communications of electronic image data are prohibitive without the use of compression.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] JPEG 2000 image compression is used by the DICOM standard for storage and transmission of medical images.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The cost and feasibility of accessing large image data sets over low or various bandwidths are further addressed by use of another DICOM standard, called JPIP, to enable efficient streaming of the JPEG 2000 compressed image data.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Electronic signal processing was revolutionized by the wide adoption of MOS technology in the 1970s.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] MOS integrated circuit technology was the basis for the first single-chip microprocessors and microcontrollers in the early 1970s, and then the first single-chip digital signal processor (DSP) chips in the late 1970s.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] DSP chips have since been widely used in digital image processing.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The discrete cosine transform (DCT) image compression algorithm has been widely implemented in DSP chips, with many companies developing DSP chips based on DCT technology.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] DCTs are widely used for encoding, decoding, video coding, audio coding, multiplexing, control signals, signaling, analog-to-digital conversion, formatting luminance and color differences, and color formats such as YUV444 and YUV411.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] DCTs are also commonly used for high-definition television (HDTV) encoder/decoder chips.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Digital image processing allows the use of much more complex algorithms, and hence, can offer both more sophisticated performance at simple tasks, and the implementation of methods which would be impossible by analogue means.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Digital filters are used to blur and sharpen digital images.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Notice that the highpass filter shows extra edges when zero padded compared to the repeated edge padding.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] MATLAB example for spatial domain highpass filtering.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] To apply the affine matrix to an image, the image is converted to a matrix in which each entry corresponds to the pixel intensity at that location.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Then each pixel's location can be represented as a vector indicating the coordinates of that pixel in the image, [*x*, *y*], where *x* and *y* are the row and column of a pixel in the image matrix.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] This allows the coordinate to be multiplied by an affine-transformation matrix, which gives the position that the pixel value will be copied to in the output image.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] However, to allow transformations that require translation transformations, 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates are needed.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The third dimension is usually set to a non-zero constant, usually 1, so that the new coordinate is [*x*, *y*, 1].
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] This allows the coordinate vector to be multiplied by a 3×3 matrix, enabling translation shifts.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Thus, the third dimension, i.e., the constant 1, allows translation.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Because matrix multiplication is associative, multiple affine transformations can be combined into a single affine transformation by multiplying the matrix of each individual transformation in the order that the transformations are done.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] This results in a single matrix that, when applied to a point vector, gives the same result as all the individual transformations performed on the vector [*x*, *y*, 1] in sequence.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Thus, a sequence of affine transformation matrices can be reduced to a single affine transformation matrix.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] For example, 2-dimensional coordinates only permit rotation about the origin (0, 0).
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] But 3-dimensional homogeneous coordinates can be used to first translate any point to (0, 0), then perform the rotation, and lastly translate the origin (0, 0) back to the original point (the opposite of the first translation).
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] These three affine transformations can be combined into a single matrix, thus allowing rotation around any point in the image.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Mathematical morphology (MM) is a nonlinear image processing framework that analyzes shapes within images by probing local pixel neighborhoods using a small, predefined function called a structuring element.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] In the context of grayscale images, MM is especially useful for denoising through dilation and erosion—primitive operators that can be combined to build more complex filters.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Here, ${\mathcal {S}}$ defines the neighborhood of relative coordinates $(m,n)$ over which local operations are computed.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The values of $B(m,n)$ bias the image during dilation and erosion.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] MM operations, such as opening and closing, are composite processes that utilize both dilation and erosion to modify the structure of an image.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] These operations are particularly useful for tasks such as noise removal, shape smoothing, and object separation.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] For example, applying opening to an image f with a structuring element B would first reduce small details (through erosion) and then restore the main shapes (through dilation).
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] This ensures that unwanted noise is removed without significantly altering the size or shape of larger objects.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] For instance, applying closing to the same image f would fill in small gaps within objects, such as connecting breaks in thin lines or closing small holes, while ensuring that the surrounding areas are not significantly affected.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Both opening and closing can be visualized as ways of refining the structure of an image: opening simplifies and removes small, unnecessary details, while closing consolidates and connects objects to form more cohesive structures.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Digital cameras generally include specialized digital image processing hardware – either dedicated chips or added circuitry on other chips – to convert the raw data from their image sensor into a color-corrected image in a standard image file format.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Additional post-processing techniques increase edge sharpness or color saturation to create more naturally looking images.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Face detection can be implemented with mathematical morphology, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), and horizontal projection.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The feature-based method of face detection uses skin tone, edge detection, face shape, and features of a face (like eyes, mouth, etc.) to achieve face detection.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] The skin tone, face shape, and all the unique elements that only the human face has can be described as features.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Normally, HSV or RGB color spaces are suitable for the skin filter.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] After filtering images with skin tone, to get the face edge, morphology and DCT are used to remove noise and fill up missing skin areas.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] DCT is to avoid the object with skin-like tone.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Since human faces always have higher texture.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] Sobel operator or other operators can be applied to detect face edge.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] To position human features like eyes, using the projection and finding the peak of the histogram of projection helps to get the detailed features like mouth, hair, and lip.
