[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] **Variability in image quality**: Variations in image quality and resolution, including blurry images and incomplete details, can hinder uniform processing across a database.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] **Object detection and Recognition**: Identifying and recognising objects within images, especially in complex scenarios with multiple objects and occlusions, poses a significant challenge.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] **Data annotation and labelling**: Labelling diverse and multiple images for machine recognition is crucial for further processing accuracy, as incorrect identification can lead to unrealistic results.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-processing] **Computational resource intensity**: Accessing adequate computational resources for image processing can be challenging and costly, hindering progress without sufficient resources.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] In computer graphics and digital imaging, **image scaling** is the resizing of a digital image.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] In video technology, the magnification of digital material is known as upscaling or resolution enhancement.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] When scaling a vector graphic image, the graphic primitives that make up the image can be rendered using geometric transformations at any resolution with no loss of image quality.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] When scaling a raster graphics image, a new image with a higher or lower number of pixels must be generated.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] In the case of decreasing the pixel number (scaling down), this usually results in a visible quality loss.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] From the standpoint of digital signal processing, the scaling of raster graphics is a two-dimensional example of sample-rate conversion, the conversion of a discrete signal from a sampling rate (in this case, the local sampling rate) to another.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Image scaling can be interpreted as a form of image resampling or image reconstruction from the view of the Nyquist sampling theorem.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] According to the theorem, downsampling to a smaller image from a higher-resolution original can only be carried out after applying a suitable 2D anti-aliasing filter to prevent aliasing artifacts.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] The image is reduced to the information that can be carried by the smaller image.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] In the case of up sampling, a reconstruction filter takes the place of the anti-aliasing filter.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] A more sophisticated approach to upscaling treats the problem as an inverse problem, solving the question of generating a plausible image that, when scaled down, would look like the input image.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] A variety of techniques have been applied for this, including optimization techniques with regularization terms and the use of machine learning from examples.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] An image size can be changed in several ways.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] One of the simpler ways of increasing image size is nearest-neighbor interpolation, replacing every pixel with the nearest pixel in the output; for upscaling, this means multiple pixels of the same color will be present.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This can preserve sharp details but also introduce jaggedness in previously smooth images.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] 'Nearest' in nearest-neighbor does not have to be the mathematical nearest.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] One common implementation is to always round toward zero.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Rounding this way produces fewer artifacts and is faster to calculate.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This algorithm is often preferred for images which have little to no smooth edges.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] A common application of this can be found in pixel art.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Bilinear interpolation works by interpolating pixel color values, introducing a continuous transition into the output even where the original material has discrete transitions.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Although this is desirable for continuous-tone images, this algorithm reduces contrast (sharp edges) in a way that may be undesirable for line art.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Bicubic interpolation yields substantially better results, with an increase in computational cost.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Sinc resampling, in theory, provides the best possible reconstruction for a perfectly bandlimited signal.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] In practice, the assumptions behind sinc resampling are not completely met by real-world digital images.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Lanczos resampling, an approximation to the sinc method, yields better results.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Bicubic interpolation can be regarded as a computationally efficient approximation to Lanczos resampling.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] One weakness of bilinear, bicubic, and related algorithms is that they sample a specific number of pixels.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] When downscaling below a certain threshold, such as more than twice for all bi-sampling algorithms, the algorithms will sample non-adjacent pixels, which results in both losing data and rough results.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] The trivial solution to this issue is box sampling, which is to consider the target pixel a box on the original image and sample all pixels inside the box.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This ensures that all input pixels contribute to the output.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] The major weakness of this algorithm is that it is hard to optimize.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Another solution to the downscale problem of bi-sampling scaling is mipmaps.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] A mipmap is a prescaled set of downscaled copies.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] When downscaling, the nearest larger mipmap is used as the origin to ensure no scaling below the useful threshold of bilinear scaling.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This algorithm is fast and easy to optimize.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] It is standard in many frameworks, such as OpenGL.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] The cost is using more image memory, exactly one-third more in the standard implementation.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Simple interpolation based on the Fourier transform pads the frequency domain with zero components (a smooth window-based approach would reduce the ringing).
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Besides the good conservation (or recovery) of details, notable are the ringing and the circular bleeding of content from the left border to the right border (and the other way around).
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Edge-directed interpolation algorithms aim to preserve edges in the image after scaling, unlike other algorithms, which can introduce staircase artifacts.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Examples of algorithms for this task include New Edge-Directed Interpolation (NEDI), Edge-Guided Image Interpolation (EGGI), Iterative Curvature-Based Interpolation (ICBI), and Directional Cubic Convolution Interpolation (DCCI).
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] A 2013 analysis found that DCCI had the best scores in peak signal-to-noise ratio and structural similarity on a series of test images.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] For magnifying computer graphics with low resolution and/or few colors (usually from 2 to 256 colors), better results can be achieved by hqx or other pixel-art scaling algorithms.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] These produce sharp edges and maintain a high level of detail.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Vector extraction, or vectorization, offers another approach.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Vectorization first creates a resolution-independent vector representation of the graphic to be scaled.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] The resulting SVG vector file can then be exported and rendered at any required resolution without quality loss, serving directly as production-ready artwork for scalable display & printing.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This technique is used by Adobe Illustrator, Live Trace, and Inkscape.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Scalable Vector Graphics are well suited to simple geometric images, while photographs do not fare well with vectorization due to their complexity.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This method uses machine learning for more detailed images, such as photographs and complex artwork.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Programs that use this method include waifu2x, Imglarger and Neural Enhance.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] AI-driven upscaling software allows detail and sharpness to be added to historical photographs, where it is not present in the original.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] The availability of AI upscaling tools has led to confusion where a person believes that the upscaled version of a blurry image is genuinely showing them the subject of the original photograph.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] In 2025 a user of the social media site X posted an AI-upscaled version of a low resolution photo of Donald Trump that they had zoomed in on, and asked if anyone could "explain what the hell is happening to his forehead".
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Experts noted that the image had been distorted by the upscaling process, and that such tools "inevitably have to invent, or at least recreate, details that were or were not there".
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Image scaling is used in, among other applications, web browsers, image editors, image and file viewers, software magnifiers, digital zoom, the process of generating thumbnail images, and when outputting images through screens or printers.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This application is the magnification of images for home theaters for HDTV-ready output devices from PAL-Resolution content, for example, from a DVD player.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Upscaling is performed in real time, and the output signal is not saved.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] As pixel-art graphics are usually low-resolution, they rely on careful placement of individual pixels, often with a limited palette of colors.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This results in graphics that rely on stylized visual cues to define complex shapes with little resolution, down to individual pixels.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] This makes scaling pixel art a particularly difficult problem.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Specialized algorithms were developed to handle pixel-art graphics, as the traditional scaling algorithms do not take perceptual cues into account.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Since a typical application is to improve the appearance of fourth-generation and earlier video games on arcade and console emulators, many are designed to run in real time for small input images at 60 frames per second.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] On fast hardware, these algorithms are suitable for gaming and other real-time image processing.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] These algorithms provide sharp, crisp graphics, while minimizing blur.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Scaling art algorithms have been implemented in a wide range of emulators such as HqMAME and DOSBox, as well as 2D game engines and game engine recreations such as ScummVM.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] They gained recognition with gamers, for whom these technologies encouraged a revival of 1980s and 1990s gaming experiences.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Such filters are currently used in commercial emulators on Xbox Live, Virtual Console, and PSN to allow classic low-resolution games to be more visually appealing on modern HD displays.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Recently released games that incorporate these filters include *Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection*, *Castlevania: The Dracula X Chronicles*, *Castlevania: Symphony of the Night*, and *Akumajō Dracula X Chi no Rondo*.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] A number of companies have developed techniques to upscale video frames in real-time, such as when they are drawn on screen in a video game.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Nvidia's deep learning super sampling (DLSS) uses deep learning to upsample lower-resolution images to a higher resolution for display on higher-resolution computer monitors.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution 1.0 (FSR) does not employ machine learning, instead using traditional hand-written algorithms to achieve spatial upscaling on traditional shading units.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] FSR 2.0 utilises temporal upscaling, again with a hand-tuned algorithm.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] FSR standardized presets are not enforced, and some titles such as *Dota 2* offer resolution sliders.
[src:sharp-imaging/image-scaling] Other technologies include Intel XeSS and Nvidia Image Scaler (NIS).
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] In information technology, **lossy compression**, or **irreversible compression**, is the class of data compression methods that uses inexact approximations and partial data discarding to represent the content.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] These techniques are used to reduce data size for storing, handling, and transmitting content.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Higher degrees of approximation create coarser images as more details are removed.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] This is opposed to lossless data compression (reversible data compression) which does not degrade the data.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The amount of data reduction possible using lossy compression is much higher than using lossless techniques.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Well-designed lossy compression technology often reduces file sizes significantly before degradation is noticed by the end-user.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Even when noticeable by the user, further data reduction may be desirable (e.g., for real-time communication or to reduce transmission times or storage needs).
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The most widely used lossy compression algorithm is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Lossy compression is most commonly used to compress multimedia data (audio, video, and images), especially in applications such as streaming media and internet telephony.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] By contrast, lossless compression is typically required for text and data files, such as bank records and text articles.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] It can be advantageous to make a master lossless file which can then be used to produce additional copies from.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] This allows one to avoid basing new compressed copies on a lossy source file, which would yield additional artifacts and further unnecessary information loss.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] It is possible to compress many types of digital data in a way that reduces the size of a computer file needed to store it, or the bandwidth needed to transmit it, with no loss of the full information contained in the original file.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] A picture, for example, is converted to a digital file by considering it to be an array of dots and specifying the color and brightness of each dot.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The original data contains a certain amount of information, and there is a lower bound to the size of a file that can still carry all the information.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Basic information theory says that there is an absolute limit in reducing the size of this data.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] When data is compressed, its entropy increases, and it cannot increase indefinitely.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] For example, a compressed ZIP file is smaller than its original, but repeatedly compressing the same file will not reduce the size to nothing.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Most compression algorithms can recognize when further compression would be pointless and would in fact increase the size of the data.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] In many cases, files or data streams contain more information than is needed.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] For example, a picture may have more detail than the eye can distinguish when reproduced at the largest size intended; likewise, an audio file does not need a lot of fine detail during a very loud passage.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Developing lossy compression techniques as closely matched to human perception as possible is a complex task.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Sometimes the ideal is a file that provides exactly the same perception as the original, with as much digital information as possible removed; other times, perceptible loss of quality is considered a valid tradeoff.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The terms "irreversible" and "reversible" are preferred over "lossy" and "lossless" respectively for some applications, such as medical image compression, to circumvent the negative implications of "loss".
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The type and amount of loss can affect the utility of the images.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Artifacts or undesirable effects of compression may be clearly discernible yet the result still useful for the intended purpose.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Or lossy compressed images may be 'visually lossless', or in the case of medical images, so-called diagnostically acceptable irreversible compression (DAIC) may have been applied.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Some forms of lossy compression can be thought of as an application of transform coding, which is a type of data compression used for digital images, digital audio signals, and digital video.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The transformation is typically used to enable better (more targeted) quantization.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Knowledge of the application is used to choose information to discard, thereby lowering its bandwidth.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The remaining information can then be compressed via a variety of methods.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] When the output is decoded, the result may not be identical to the original input, but is expected to be close enough for the purpose of the application.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The most common form of lossy compression is a transform coding method, the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first published by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] DCT is the most widely used form of lossy compression, for popular image compression formats (such as JPEG), video coding standards (such as MPEG and H.264/AVC) and audio compression formats (such as MP3 and AAC).
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] In the case of audio data, a popular form of transform coding is perceptual coding, which transforms the raw data to a domain that more accurately reflects the information content.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] For example, rather than expressing a sound file as the amplitude levels over time, one may express it as the frequency spectrum over time, which corresponds more accurately to human audio perception.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] This is because uncompressed audio can only reduce file size by lowering bit rate or depth, whereas compressing audio can reduce size while maintaining bit rate and depth.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] This compression becomes a selective loss of the least significant data, rather than losing data across the board.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Further, a transform coding may provide a better domain for manipulating or otherwise editing the data – for example, equalization of audio is most naturally expressed in the frequency domain (boost the bass, for instance) rather than in the raw time domain.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] From this point of view, perceptual encoding is not essentially about *discarding* data, but rather about a *better representation* of data.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Another use is for backward compatibility and graceful degradation: in color television, encoding color via a luminance-chrominance transform domain (such as YUV) means that black-and-white sets display the luminance, while ignoring the color information.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Lossy compression formats suffer from generation loss: repeatedly compressing and decompressing the file will cause it to progressively lose quality.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] This is in contrast with lossless data compression, where data will not be lost via the use of such a procedure.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Information-theoretical foundations for lossy data compression are provided by rate-distortion theory.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Much like the use of probability in optimal coding theory, rate-distortion theory heavily draws on Bayesian estimation and decision theory in order to model perceptual distortion and even aesthetic judgment.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] In some systems the two techniques are combined, with transform codecs being used to compress the error signals generated by the predictive stage.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The advantage of lossy methods over lossless methods is that in some cases a lossy method can produce a much smaller compressed file than any lossless method, while still meeting the requirements of the application.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Lossy methods are most often used for compressing sound, images or videos.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] This is because these types of data are intended for human interpretation where the mind can easily "fill in the blanks" or see past very minor errors or inconsistencies – ideally lossy compression is transparent (imperceptible), which can be verified via an ABX test.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Data files using lossy compression are smaller in size and thus cost less to store and to transmit over the Internet, a crucial consideration for streaming video services such as Netflix and streaming audio services such as Spotify.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] When a user acquires a lossily compressed file, (for example, to reduce download time) the retrieved file can be quite different from the original at the bit level while being indistinguishable to the human ear or eye for most practical purposes.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Many compression methods focus on the idiosyncrasies of human physiology, taking into account, for instance, that the human eye can see only certain wavelengths of light.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The psychoacoustic model describes how sound can be highly compressed without degrading perceived quality.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Flaws caused by lossy compression that are noticeable to the human eye or ear are known as compression artifacts.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The compression ratio (that is, the size of the compressed file compared to that of the uncompressed file) of lossy video codecs is nearly always far superior to that of the audio and still-image equivalents.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] An important caveat about lossy compression (formally transcoding), is that editing lossily compressed files causes digital generation loss from the re-encoding.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] This can be avoided by only producing lossy files from (lossless) originals and only editing (copies of) original files, such as images in raw image format instead of JPEG.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] If data which has been compressed lossily is decoded and compressed losslessly, the size of the result can be comparable with the size of the data before lossy compression, but the data already lost cannot be recovered.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] When deciding to use lossy conversion without keeping the original, format conversion may be needed in the future to achieve compatibility with software or devices (format shifting), or to avoid paying patent royalties for decoding or distribution of compressed files.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] By modifying the compressed data directly without decoding and re-encoding, some editing of lossily compressed files without degradation of quality is possible.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Editing which reduces the file size as if it had been compressed to a greater degree, but without more loss than this, is sometimes also possible.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The primary programs for lossless editing of JPEGs are `jpegtran`, and the derived `exiftran` (which also preserves Exif information), and Jpegcrop (which provides a Windows interface).
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] These allow the image to be cropped, rotated, flipped, and flopped, or even converted to grayscale (by dropping the chrominance channel).
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] While unwanted information is destroyed, the quality of the remaining portion is unchanged.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Some other transforms are possible to some extent, such as joining images with the same encoding (composing side by side, as on a grid) or pasting images such as logos onto existing images (both via Jpegjoin), or scaling.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] The freeware Windows-only IrfanView has some lossless JPEG operations in its `JPG_TRANSFORM` plugin.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Metadata, such as ID3 tags, Vorbis comments, or Exif information, can usually be modified or removed without modifying the underlying data.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Some well-known designs that have this capability include JPEG 2000 for still images and H.264/MPEG-4 AVC based Scalable Video Coding for video.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Such schemes have also been standardized for older designs as well, such as JPEG images with progressive encoding, and MPEG-2 and MPEG-4 Part 2 video, although those prior schemes had limited success in terms of adoption into real-world common usage.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Similar techniques are used in mipmaps, pyramid representations, and more sophisticated scale space methods.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Some audio formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction which when combined reproduce the original signal; the correction can be stripped, leaving a smaller, lossily compressed, file.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, OptimFROG DualStream, and DTS-HD Master Audio in lossless (XLL) mode).
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Researchers have performed lossy compression on text by either using a thesaurus to substitute short words for long ones, or generative text techniques, although these sometimes fall into the related category of lossy data conversion.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] A general kind of lossy compression is to lower the resolution of an image, as in image scaling, particularly decimation.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] One may also remove less "lower information" parts of an image, such as by seam carving.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Many media transforms, such as Gaussian blur, are, like lossy compression, irreversible: the original signal cannot be reconstructed from the transformed signal.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] However, in general these will have the same size as the original, and are not a form of compression.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Lowering resolution has practical uses, as the NASA New Horizons craft transmitted thumbnails of its encounter with Pluto-Charon before it sent the higher resolution images.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Another solution for slow connections is the usage of Image interlacing which progressively defines the image.
[src:sharp-imaging/lossy-compression] Thus a partial transmission is enough to preview the final image, in a lower resolution version, without creating a scaled and a full version too.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] The typical use case for this high speed Node-API module is to convert large images in common formats to smaller, web-friendly JPEG, PNG, WebP, GIF and AVIF images of varying dimensions.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] It can be used with all JavaScript runtimes that provide support for Node-API v9, including Node.js (>= 20.9.0), Deno and Bun.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] Resizing an image is typically 4x-5x faster than using the quickest ImageMagick and GraphicsMagick settings due to its use of libvips.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] Colour spaces, embedded ICC profiles and alpha transparency channels are all handled correctly.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] Lanczos resampling ensures quality is not sacrificed for speed.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] As well as image resizing, operations such as rotation, extraction, compositing and gamma correction are available.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] Most modern macOS, Windows and Linux systems do not require any additional install or runtime dependencies.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] Visit sharp.pixelplumbing.com for complete installation instructions, API documentation, benchmark tests and changelog.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] A guide for contributors covers reporting bugs, requesting features and submitting code changes.
[src:sharp-imaging/lovell-sharp] Copyright 2013 Lovell Fuller and others.
